## .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

### Critical Breaking Change

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8. `ThreadAbortException` is never raised. Your `Stop()` method will crash and your catch block is dead code.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();

    public void Start()
    {
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit loop; finally still runs
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask Stop()
    {
        await _cts.CancelAsync();          // signal cancellation (non-throwing)
        if (_workerTask is not null)
        {
            // Wait up to 2s for graceful exit, then move on
            await _workerTask.WaitAsync(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2))
                             .ConfigureAwait(ConfigureAwaitOptions.SuppressThrowing);
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Details |
|---|---|
| **`Thread.Abort()` gone** | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. Replace with `CancellationToken` cooperative cancellation. |
| **`ThreadAbortException` never thrown** | Catch `OperationCanceledException` instead. Unlike `ThreadAbortException`, it does **not** auto-rethrow — no `ResetAbort()` equivalent needed. |
| **Blocking calls ignore cancellation** | If `GetNextItem()` blocks on a `Monitor`, `ManualResetEvent`, etc., cancellation won't interrupt it. Migrate to async APIs (`SemaphoreSlim.WaitAsync`, `Channel<T>.ReadAsync`) that accept `CancellationToken`. |
| **`volatile bool` flag insufficient** | A `volatile bool` can't interrupt a blocked call. `CancellationToken` integrates with async/await, `WaitHandle`, and `BlockingCollection`. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` for shutdown** | Replace with `await Task.WaitAsync(timeout)` — non-blocking and deterministic. |

### If You Can't Go Fully Async

```csharp
// Synchronous version using BlockingCollection + CancellationToken
private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        try
        {
            // BlockingCollection.Take accepts a token — unblocks on cancel
            var item = _queue.Take(token);
            ProcessItem(item);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            break;
        }
        finally
        {
            FlushBuffers();
        }
    }
}
```

### Also Consider: `BackgroundService`

For hosted apps (ASP.NET Core, Worker Services), inherit from `BackgroundService` — it manages the lifecycle and cancellation token for you:

```csharp
public class Processor : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            var item = await GetNextItemAsync(stoppingToken);
            await ProcessItemAsync(item, stoppingToken);
        }
    }
}
// Register: builder.Services.AddHostedService<Processor>();
```

**Bottom line:** The core mental model shift is from *forceful abort* to *cooperative cancellation*. Every blocking call must accept and respect a `CancellationToken`, or your shutdown will hang.
